<DOC><DOCNO> AP881010-0259 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1155EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-TennecoSale     10-10 0299</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Tenneco Sale,0309</SECOND><HEAD>Tenneco Expects Oil Company Sale Will Gross $7.3 Billion</HEAD><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tenneco Inc. announced today it has entered intodefinitive contracts with several buyers for the sale of almost allof its oil and gas businesses and that it expects the transactionsto gross more than $7.3 billion.   Tenneco did not name the buyers. However, Mesa LimitedPartnership, controlled by Texas oilman T. Boone Pickens, announcedit has agreed to buy Tenneco's oil and gas production in itsmid-continent division for $715 million in cash.   In addition, Seagull Energy Corp. announced today it had signedletters of intent to buy Tenneco's Houston Oil andamp; Minerals Corp. for$16.4 million.   It was also announced today that Seagull has agreed to buy theassets of the Houston Oil Trust for $35.3 million and Houston OilRoyalty Trust for $4.5 million in separate transactions.   Negotiations are continuing for certain minor portions ofTenneco's oil and gas segment, but the company said it expectstotal gross proceeds from the sales to exceed the $7.3 billionmark, according to a statement released today.   Although the Houston-based company did not disclose any detailsabout the agreements, it said more information would be releasedTuesday following a board meeting.   Tenneco, the nation's 10th largest oil company, had previouslysaid it expects all of the transactions to be closed by the end ofthe year.   The company announced in May it was getting out of the petroleumexploration and production business, which represents about 20percent of its assets, and would concentrate on its pipeline andother industrial businesses7.   When Tenneco made the announcement, it said proceeds would beused to help pay its hefty $8.5 billion debt. Analysts haveestimated that the sale could fetch between $5 billion and $7billion.</TEXT></DOC>